45     /* This file implements the Memcheck instrumentation, and in
46        particular contains the core of its undefined value detection
47        machinery.  For a comprehensive background of the terminology,
48        algorithms and rationale used herein, read:
49     
50          Using Valgrind to detect undefined value errors with
51          bit-precision
52     
53          Julian Seward and Nicholas Nethercote
54     
55          2005 USENIX Annual Technical Conference (General Track),
56          Anaheim, CA, USA, April 10-15, 2005.
57     
58        ----
59     
60        Here is as good a place as any to record exactly when V bits are and
61        should be checked, why, and what function is responsible.
62     
63        
64        Memcheck complains when an undefined value is used:
65     
66        1. In the condition of a conditional branch.  Because it could cause
67           incorrect control flow, and thus cause incorrect externally-visible
68           behaviour.  [mc_translate.c:complainIfUndefined]
69     
70        2. As an argument to a system call, or as the value that specifies
71           the system call number.  Because it could cause an incorrect
72           externally-visible side effect.  [mc_translate.c:mc_pre_reg_read]
73     
74        3. As the address in a load or store.  Because it could cause an
75           incorrect value to be used later, which could cause externally-visible
76           behaviour (eg. via incorrect control flow or an incorrect system call
77           argument)  [complainIfUndefined]
78     
79        4. As the target address of a branch.  Because it could cause incorrect
80           control flow.  [complainIfUndefined]
81     
82        5. As an argument to setenv, unsetenv, or putenv.  Because it could put
83           an incorrect value into the external environment.
84           [mc_replace_strmem.c:VG_WRAP_FUNCTION_ZU(*, *env)]
85     
86        6. As the index in a GETI or PUTI operation.  I'm not sure why... (njn).
87           [complainIfUndefined]
88     
89        7. As an argument to the VALGRIND_CHECK_MEM_IS_DEFINED and
90           VALGRIND_CHECK_VALUE_IS_DEFINED client requests.  Because the user
91           requested it.  [in memcheck.h]
92     
93     
94        Memcheck also complains, but should not, when an undefined value is used:
95     
96        8. As the shift value in certain SIMD shift operations (but not in the
97           standard integer shift operations).  This inconsistency is due to
98           historical reasons.)  [complainIfUndefined]
99     
100     
101        Memcheck does not complain, but should, when an undefined value is used:
102     
103        9. As an input to a client request.  Because the client request may
104           affect the visible behaviour -- see bug #144362 for an example
105           involving the malloc replacements in vg_replace_malloc.c and
106           VALGRIND_NON_SIMD_CALL* requests, where an uninitialised argument
107           isn't identified.  That bug report also has some info on how to solve
108           the problem.  [valgrind.h:VALGRIND_DO_CLIENT_REQUEST]
109     
110     
111        In practice, 1 and 2 account for the vast majority of cases.
112     */

126     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
127     /*--- Memcheck running state, and tmp management.          ---*/
128     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
129     
130     /* Carries info about a particular tmp.  The tmp's number is not
131        recorded, as this is implied by (equal to) its index in the tmpMap
132        in MCEnv.  The tmp's type is also not recorded, as this is present
133        in MCEnv.sb->tyenv.
134     
135        When .kind is Orig, .shadowV and .shadowB may give the identities
136        of the temps currently holding the associated definedness (shadowV)
137        and origin (shadowB) values, or these may be IRTemp_INVALID if code
138        to compute such values has not yet been emitted.
139     
140        When .kind is VSh or BSh then the tmp is holds a V- or B- value,
141        and so .shadowV and .shadowB must be IRTemp_INVALID, since it is
142        illogical for a shadow tmp itself to be shadowed.
143     */
144     typedef
145        enum { Orig=1, VSh=2, BSh=3 }
146        TempKind;
147     
148     typedef
149        struct {
150           TempKind kind;
151           IRTemp   shadowV;
152           IRTemp   shadowB;
153        }
154        TempMapEnt;
155     
156     
157     /* Carries around state during memcheck instrumentation. */
158     typedef
159        struct _MCEnv {
160           /* MODIFIED: the superblock being constructed.  IRStmts are
161              added. */
162           IRSB* sb;
163           Bool  trace;
164     
165           /* MODIFIED: a table [0 .. #temps_in_sb-1] which gives the
166              current kind and possibly shadow temps for each temp in the
167              IRSB being constructed.  Note that it does not contain the
168              type of each tmp.  If you want to know the type, look at the
169              relevant entry in sb->tyenv.  It follows that at all times
170              during the instrumentation process, the valid indices for
171              tmpMap and sb->tyenv are identical, being 0 .. N-1 where N is
172              total number of Orig, V- and B- temps allocated so far.
173     
174              The reason for this strange split (types in one place, all
175              other info in another) is that we need the types to be
176              attached to sb so as to make it possible to do
177              "typeOfIRExpr(mce->bb->tyenv, ...)" at various places in the
178              instrumentation process. */
179           XArray* /* of TempMapEnt */ tmpMap;
180     
181           /* MODIFIED: indicates whether "bogus" literals have so far been
182              found.  Starts off False, and may change to True. */
183           Bool    bogusLiterals;
184     
185           /* READONLY: the guest layout.  This indicates which parts of
186              the guest state should be regarded as 'always defined'. */
187           VexGuestLayout* layout;
188     
189           /* READONLY: the host word type.  Needed for constructing
190              arguments of type 'HWord' to be passed to helper functions.
191              Ity_I32 or Ity_I64 only. */
192           IRType hWordTy;
193        }
194        MCEnv;
195     
196     /* SHADOW TMP MANAGEMENT.  Shadow tmps are allocated lazily (on
197        demand), as they are encountered.  This is for two reasons.
198     
199        (1) (less important reason): Many original tmps are unused due to
200        initial IR optimisation, and we do not want to spaces in tables
201        tracking them.
202     
203        Shadow IRTemps are therefore allocated on demand.  mce.tmpMap is a
204        table indexed [0 .. n_types-1], which gives the current shadow for
205        each original tmp, or INVALID_IRTEMP if none is so far assigned.
206        It is necessary to support making multiple assignments to a shadow
207        -- specifically, after testing a shadow for definedness, it needs
208        to be made defined.  But IR's SSA property disallows this.  
209     
210        (2) (more important reason): Therefore, when a shadow needs to get
211        a new value, a new temporary is created, the value is assigned to
212        that, and the tmpMap is updated to reflect the new binding.
213     
214        A corollary is that if the tmpMap maps a given tmp to
215        IRTemp_INVALID and we are hoping to read that shadow tmp, it means
216        there's a read-before-write error in the original tmps.  The IR
217        sanity checker should catch all such anomalies, however.  
218     */
219     
220     /* Create a new IRTemp of type 'ty' and kind 'kind', and add it to
221        both the table in mce->sb and to our auxiliary mapping.  Note that
222        newTemp may cause mce->tmpMap to resize, hence previous results
223        from VG_(indexXA)(mce->tmpMap) are invalidated. */
224     static IRTemp newTemp ( MCEnv* mce, IRType ty, TempKind kind )
225     {
226        Word       newIx;
227        TempMapEnt ent;
228        IRTemp     tmp = newIRTemp(mce->sb->tyenv, ty);
229        ent.kind    = kind;
230        ent.shadowV = IRTemp_INVALID;
231        ent.shadowB = IRTemp_INVALID;
232        newIx = VG_(addToXA)( mce->tmpMap, &ent );
233        tl_assert(newIx == (Word)tmp);
234        return tmp;
235     }
236     
237     
238     /* Find the tmp currently shadowing the given original tmp.  If none
239        so far exists, allocate one.  */
240     static IRTemp findShadowTmpV ( MCEnv* mce, IRTemp orig )
241     {
242        TempMapEnt* ent;
243        /* VG_(indexXA) range-checks 'orig', hence no need to check
244           here. */
245        ent = (TempMapEnt*)VG_(indexXA)( mce->tmpMap, (Word)orig );
246        tl_assert(ent->kind == Orig);
247        if (ent->shadowV == IRTemp_INVALID) {
248           IRTemp tmpV
249             = newTemp( mce, shadowTypeV(mce->sb->tyenv->types[orig]), VSh );
250           /* newTemp may cause mce->tmpMap to resize, hence previous results
251              from VG_(indexXA) are invalid. */
252           ent = (TempMapEnt*)VG_(indexXA)( mce->tmpMap, (Word)orig );
253           tl_assert(ent->kind == Orig);
254           tl_assert(ent->shadowV == IRTemp_INVALID);
255           ent->shadowV = tmpV;
256        }
257        return ent->shadowV;
258     }
259     
260     /* Allocate a new shadow for the given original tmp.  This means any
261        previous shadow is abandoned.  This is needed because it is
262        necessary to give a new value to a shadow once it has been tested
263        for undefinedness, but unfortunately IR's SSA property disallows
264        this.  Instead we must abandon the old shadow, allocate a new one
265        and use that instead.
266     
267        This is the same as findShadowTmpV, except we don't bother to see
268        if a shadow temp already existed -- we simply allocate a new one
269        regardless. */
270     static void newShadowTmpV ( MCEnv* mce, IRTemp orig )
271     {
272        TempMapEnt* ent;
273        /* VG_(indexXA) range-checks 'orig', hence no need to check
274           here. */
275        ent = (TempMapEnt*)VG_(indexXA)( mce->tmpMap, (Word)orig );
276        tl_assert(ent->kind == Orig);
277        if (1) {
278           IRTemp tmpV
279             = newTemp( mce, shadowTypeV(mce->sb->tyenv->types[orig]), VSh );
280           /* newTemp may cause mce->tmpMap to resize, hence previous results
281              from VG_(indexXA) are invalid. */
282           ent = (TempMapEnt*)VG_(indexXA)( mce->tmpMap, (Word)orig );
283           tl_assert(ent->kind == Orig);
284           ent->shadowV = tmpV;
285        }
286     }

289     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
290     /*--- IRAtoms -- a subset of IRExprs                       ---*/
291     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
292     
293     /* An atom is either an IRExpr_Const or an IRExpr_Tmp, as defined by
294        isIRAtom() in libvex_ir.h.  Because this instrumenter expects flat
295        input, most of this code deals in atoms.  Usefully, a value atom
296        always has a V-value which is also an atom: constants are shadowed
297        by constants, and temps are shadowed by the corresponding shadow
298        temporary. */
299     
300     typedef  IRExpr  IRAtom;
301     
302     /* (used for sanity checks only): is this an atom which looks
303        like it's from original code? */
304     static Bool isOriginalAtom ( MCEnv* mce, IRAtom* a1 )
305     {
306        if (a1->tag == Iex_Const)
307           return True;
308        if (a1->tag == Iex_RdTmp) {
309           TempMapEnt* ent = VG_(indexXA)( mce->tmpMap, a1->Iex.RdTmp.tmp );
310           return ent->kind == Orig;
311        }
312        return False;
313     }
314     
315     /* (used for sanity checks only): is this an atom which looks
316        like it's from shadow code? */
317     static Bool isShadowAtom ( MCEnv* mce, IRAtom* a1 )
318     {
319        if (a1->tag == Iex_Const)
320           return True;
321        if (a1->tag == Iex_RdTmp) {
322           TempMapEnt* ent = VG_(indexXA)( mce->tmpMap, a1->Iex.RdTmp.tmp );
323           return ent->kind == VSh || ent->kind == BSh;
324        }
325        return False;
326     }
327     
328     /* (used for sanity checks only): check that both args are atoms and
329        are identically-kinded. */
330     static Bool sameKindedAtoms ( IRAtom* a1, IRAtom* a2 )
331     {
332        if (a1->tag == Iex_RdTmp && a2->tag == Iex_RdTmp)
333           return True;
334        if (a1->tag == Iex_Const && a2->tag == Iex_Const)
335           return True;
336        return False;
337     }

340     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
341     /*--- Type management                                      ---*/
342     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
343     
344     /* Shadow state is always accessed using integer types.  This returns
345        an integer type with the same size (as per sizeofIRType) as the
346        given type.  The only valid shadow types are Bit, I8, I16, I32,
347        I64, I128, V128. */
348     
349     static IRType shadowTypeV ( IRType ty )
350     {
351        switch (ty) {
352           case Ity_I1:
353           case Ity_I8:
354           case Ity_I16:
355           case Ity_I32: 
356           case Ity_I64: 
357           case Ity_I128: return ty;
358           case Ity_F32:  return Ity_I32;
359           case Ity_F64:  return Ity_I64;
360           case Ity_F128: return Ity_I128;
361           case Ity_V128: return Ity_V128;
362           default: ppIRType(ty); 
363                    VG_(tool_panic)("memcheck:shadowTypeV");
364        }
365     }
366     
367     /* Produce a 'defined' value of the given shadow type.  Should only be
368        supplied shadow types (Bit/I8/I16/I32/UI64). */
369     static IRExpr* definedOfType ( IRType ty ) {
370        switch (ty) {
371           case Ity_I1:   return IRExpr_Const(IRConst_U1(False));
372           case Ity_I8:   return IRExpr_Const(IRConst_U8(0));
373           case Ity_I16:  return IRExpr_Const(IRConst_U16(0));
374           case Ity_I32:  return IRExpr_Const(IRConst_U32(0));
375           case Ity_I64:  return IRExpr_Const(IRConst_U64(0));
376           case Ity_I128: return i128_const_zero();
377           case Ity_V128: return IRExpr_Const(IRConst_V128(0x0000));
378           default:       VG_(tool_panic)("memcheck:definedOfType");
379        }
380     }

387     /* add stmt to a bb */
388     static inline void stmt ( HChar cat, MCEnv* mce, IRStmt* st ) {
389        if (mce->trace) {
390           VG_(printf)("  %c: ", cat);
391           ppIRStmt(st);
392           VG_(printf)("\n");
393        }
394        addStmtToIRSB(mce->sb, st);
395     }
396     
397     /* assign value to tmp */
398     static inline 
399     void assign ( HChar cat, MCEnv* mce, IRTemp tmp, IRExpr* expr ) {
400        stmt(cat, mce, IRStmt_WrTmp(tmp,expr));
401     }
402     
403     /* build various kinds of expressions */
404     #define triop(_op, _arg1, _arg2, _arg3) \
405                                      IRExpr_Triop((_op),(_arg1),(_arg2),(_arg3))
406     #define binop(_op, _arg1, _arg2) IRExpr_Binop((_op),(_arg1),(_arg2))
407     #define unop(_op, _arg)          IRExpr_Unop((_op),(_arg))
408     #define mkU8(_n)                 IRExpr_Const(IRConst_U8(_n))
409     #define mkU16(_n)                IRExpr_Const(IRConst_U16(_n))
410     #define mkU32(_n)                IRExpr_Const(IRConst_U32(_n))
411     #define mkU64(_n)                IRExpr_Const(IRConst_U64(_n))
412     #define mkV128(_n)               IRExpr_Const(IRConst_V128(_n))
413     #define mkexpr(_tmp)             IRExpr_RdTmp((_tmp))
414     
415     /* Bind the given expression to a new temporary, and return the
416        temporary.  This effectively converts an arbitrary expression into
417        an atom.
418     
419        'ty' is the type of 'e' and hence the type that the new temporary
420        needs to be.  But passing it in is redundant, since we can deduce
421        the type merely by inspecting 'e'.  So at least use that fact to
422        assert that the two types agree. */
423     static IRAtom* assignNew ( HChar cat, MCEnv* mce, IRType ty, IRExpr* e )
424     {
425        TempKind k;
426        IRTemp   t;
427        IRType   tyE = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, e);
428        tl_assert(tyE == ty); /* so 'ty' is redundant (!) */
429        switch (cat) {
430           case 'V': k = VSh;  break;
431           case 'B': k = BSh;  break;
432           case 'C': k = Orig; break; 
433                     /* happens when we are making up new "orig"
434                        expressions, for IRCAS handling */
435           default: tl_assert(0);
436        }
437        t = newTemp(mce, ty, k);
438        assign(cat, mce, t, e);
439        return mkexpr(t);
440     }

461     static IRAtom* mkDifD8 ( MCEnv* mce, IRAtom* a1, IRAtom* a2 ) {
462        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,a1));
463        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,a2));
464        return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I8, binop(Iop_And8, a1, a2));
465     }

517     static IRAtom* mkUifU128 ( MCEnv* mce, IRAtom* a1, IRAtom* a2 ) {
518        IRAtom *tmp1, *tmp2, *tmp3, *tmp4, *tmp5, *tmp6;
519        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,a1));
520        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,a2));
521        tmp1 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, unop(Iop_128to64, a1));
522        tmp2 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, unop(Iop_128HIto64, a1));
523        tmp3 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, unop(Iop_128to64, a2));
524        tmp4 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, unop(Iop_128HIto64, a2));
525        tmp5 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, binop(Iop_Or64, tmp1, tmp3));
526        tmp6 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, binop(Iop_Or64, tmp2, tmp4));
527     
528        return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I128, binop(Iop_64HLto128, tmp6, tmp5));
529     }
530     
531     static IRAtom* mkUifUV128 ( MCEnv* mce, IRAtom* a1, IRAtom* a2 ) {
532        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,a1));
533        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,a2));
534        return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_V128, binop(Iop_OrV128, a1, a2));
535     }

537     static IRAtom* mkUifU ( MCEnv* mce, IRType vty, IRAtom* a1, IRAtom* a2 ) {
538        switch (vty) {
539           case Ity_I8:   return mkUifU8(mce, a1, a2);
540           case Ity_I16:  return mkUifU16(mce, a1, a2);
541           case Ity_I32:  return mkUifU32(mce, a1, a2);
542           case Ity_I64:  return mkUifU64(mce, a1, a2);
543           case Ity_I128: return mkUifU128(mce, a1, a2);
544           case Ity_V128: return mkUifUV128(mce, a1, a2);
545           default:
546              VG_(printf)("\n"); ppIRType(vty); VG_(printf)("\n");
547              VG_(tool_panic)("memcheck:mkUifU");
548        }
549     }

551     /* --------- The Left-family of operations. --------- */

681     /* --------- Pessimising casts. --------- */
682     
683     /* The function returns an expression of type DST_TY. If any of the VBITS
684        is undefined (value == 1) the resulting expression has all bits set to
685        1. Otherwise, all bits are 0. */
686     
687     static IRAtom* mkPCastTo( MCEnv* mce, IRType dst_ty, IRAtom* vbits ) 
688     {
689        IRType  src_ty;
690        IRAtom* tmp1;
691        /* Note, dst_ty is a shadow type, not an original type. */
692        /* First of all, collapse vbits down to a single bit. */
693        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vbits));
694        src_ty = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, vbits);
695     
696        /* Fast-track some common cases */
697        if (src_ty == Ity_I32 && dst_ty == Ity_I32)
698           return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I32, unop(Iop_CmpwNEZ32, vbits));
699     
700        if (src_ty == Ity_I64 && dst_ty == Ity_I64)
701           return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, unop(Iop_CmpwNEZ64, vbits));
702     
703        if (src_ty == Ity_I32 && dst_ty == Ity_I64) {
704           IRAtom* tmp = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I32, unop(Iop_CmpwNEZ32, vbits));
705           return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, binop(Iop_32HLto64, tmp, tmp));
706        }
707     
708        /* Else do it the slow way .. */
709        tmp1   = NULL;
710        switch (src_ty) {
711           case Ity_I1:
712              tmp1 = vbits;
713              break;
714           case Ity_I8: 
715              tmp1 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I1, unop(Iop_CmpNEZ8, vbits));
716              break;
717           case Ity_I16: 
718              tmp1 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I1, unop(Iop_CmpNEZ16, vbits));
719              break;
720           case Ity_I32: 
721              tmp1 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I1, unop(Iop_CmpNEZ32, vbits));
722              break;
723           case Ity_I64: 
724              tmp1 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I1, unop(Iop_CmpNEZ64, vbits));
725              break;
726           case Ity_I128: {
727              /* Gah.  Chop it in half, OR the halves together, and compare
728                 that with zero. */
729              IRAtom* tmp2 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, unop(Iop_128HIto64, vbits));
730              IRAtom* tmp3 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, unop(Iop_128to64, vbits));
731              IRAtom* tmp4 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, binop(Iop_Or64, tmp2, tmp3));
732              tmp1         = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I1, 
733                                            unop(Iop_CmpNEZ64, tmp4));
734              break;
735           }
736           default:
737              ppIRType(src_ty);
738              VG_(tool_panic)("mkPCastTo(1)");
739        }
740        tl_assert(tmp1);
741        /* Now widen up to the dst type. */
742        switch (dst_ty) {
743           case Ity_I1:
744              return tmp1;
745           case Ity_I8: 
746              return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I8, unop(Iop_1Sto8, tmp1));
747           case Ity_I16: 
748              return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I16, unop(Iop_1Sto16, tmp1));
749           case Ity_I32: 
750              return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I32, unop(Iop_1Sto32, tmp1));
751           case Ity_I64: 
752              return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, unop(Iop_1Sto64, tmp1));
753           case Ity_V128:
754              tmp1 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64,  unop(Iop_1Sto64, tmp1));
755              tmp1 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_V128, binop(Iop_64HLtoV128, tmp1, tmp1));
756              return tmp1;
757           case Ity_I128:
758              tmp1 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64,  unop(Iop_1Sto64, tmp1));
759              tmp1 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I128, binop(Iop_64HLto128, tmp1, tmp1));
760              return tmp1;
761           default: 
762              ppIRType(dst_ty);
763              VG_(tool_panic)("mkPCastTo(2)");
764        }
765     }
766     
767     /* --------- Accurate interpretation of CmpEQ/CmpNE. --------- */
768     /* 
769        Normally, we can do CmpEQ/CmpNE by doing UifU on the arguments, and
770        PCasting to Ity_U1.  However, sometimes it is necessary to be more
771        accurate.  The insight is that the result is defined if two
772        corresponding bits can be found, one from each argument, so that
773        both bits are defined but are different -- that makes EQ say "No"
774        and NE say "Yes".  Hence, we compute an improvement term and DifD
775        it onto the "normal" (UifU) result.
776     
777        The result is:
778     
779        PCastTo<1> (
780           -- naive version
781           PCastTo<sz>( UifU<sz>(vxx, vyy) )
782     
783           `DifD<sz>`
784     
785           -- improvement term
786           PCastTo<sz>( PCast<sz>( CmpEQ<sz> ( vec, 1...1 ) ) )
787        )
788     
789        where
790          vec contains 0 (defined) bits where the corresponding arg bits 
791          are defined but different, and 1 bits otherwise.
792     
793          vec = Or<sz>( vxx,   // 0 iff bit defined
794                        vyy,   // 0 iff bit defined
795                        Not<sz>(Xor<sz>( xx, yy )) // 0 iff bits different
796                      )
797                         
798          If any bit of vec is 0, the result is defined and so the 
799          improvement term should produce 0...0, else it should produce
800          1...1.
801     
802          Hence require for the improvement term:
803     
804             if vec == 1...1 then 1...1 else 0...0
805          ->
806             PCast<sz>( CmpEQ<sz> ( vec, 1...1 ) )
807     
808        This was extensively re-analysed and checked on 6 July 05.
809     */
810     static IRAtom* expensiveCmpEQorNE ( MCEnv*  mce,
811                                         IRType  ty,
812                                         IRAtom* vxx, IRAtom* vyy, 
813                                         IRAtom* xx,  IRAtom* yy )
814     {
815        IRAtom *naive, *vec, *improvement_term;
816        IRAtom *improved, *final_cast, *top;
817        IROp   opDIFD, opUIFU, opXOR, opNOT, opCMP, opOR;
818     
819        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vxx));
820        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vyy));
821        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,xx));
822        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,yy));
823        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(vxx,xx));
824        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(vyy,yy));
825      
826        switch (ty) {
827           case Ity_I32:
828              opOR   = Iop_Or32;
829              opDIFD = Iop_And32;
830              opUIFU = Iop_Or32;
831              opNOT  = Iop_Not32;
832              opXOR  = Iop_Xor32;
833              opCMP  = Iop_CmpEQ32;
834              top    = mkU32(0xFFFFFFFF);
835              break;
836           case Ity_I64:
837              opOR   = Iop_Or64;
838              opDIFD = Iop_And64;
839              opUIFU = Iop_Or64;
840              opNOT  = Iop_Not64;
841              opXOR  = Iop_Xor64;
842              opCMP  = Iop_CmpEQ64;
843              top    = mkU64(0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFULL);
844              break;
845           default:
846              VG_(tool_panic)("expensiveCmpEQorNE");
847        }
848     
849        naive 
850           = mkPCastTo(mce,ty,
851                       assignNew('V', mce, ty, binop(opUIFU, vxx, vyy)));
852     
853        vec 
854           = assignNew(
855                'V', mce,ty, 
856                binop( opOR,
857                       assignNew('V', mce,ty, binop(opOR, vxx, vyy)),
858                       assignNew(
859                          'V', mce,ty, 
860                          unop( opNOT,
861                                assignNew('V', mce,ty, binop(opXOR, xx, yy))))));
862     
863        improvement_term
864           = mkPCastTo( mce,ty,
865                        assignNew('V', mce,Ity_I1, binop(opCMP, vec, top)));
866     
867        improved
868           = assignNew( 'V', mce,ty, binop(opDIFD, naive, improvement_term) );
869     
870        final_cast
871           = mkPCastTo( mce, Ity_I1, improved );
872     
873        return final_cast;
874     }
875     
876     
877     /* --------- Semi-accurate interpretation of CmpORD. --------- */
878     
879     /* CmpORD32{S,U} does PowerPC-style 3-way comparisons:
880     
881           CmpORD32S(x,y) = 1<<3   if  x <s y
882                          = 1<<2   if  x >s y
883                          = 1<<1   if  x == y
884     
885        and similarly the unsigned variant.  The default interpretation is:
886     
887           CmpORD32{S,U}#(x,y,x#,y#) = PCast(x# `UifU` y#)  
888                                       & (7<<1)
889     
890        The "& (7<<1)" reflects the fact that all result bits except 3,2,1
891        are zero and therefore defined (viz, zero).
892     
893        Also deal with a special case better:
894     
895           CmpORD32S(x,0)
896     
897        Here, bit 3 (LT) of the result is a copy of the top bit of x and
898        will be defined even if the rest of x isn't.  In which case we do:
899     
900           CmpORD32S#(x,x#,0,{impliedly 0}#)
901              = PCast(x#) & (3<<1)      -- standard interp for GT#,EQ#
902                | (x# >>u 31) << 3      -- LT# = x#[31]
903     
904        Analogous handling for CmpORD64{S,U}.
905     */
906     static Bool isZeroU32 ( IRAtom* e )
907     {
908        return
909           toBool( e->tag == Iex_Const
910                   && e->Iex.Const.con->tag == Ico_U32
911                   && e->Iex.Const.con->Ico.U32 == 0 );
912     }
913     
914     static Bool isZeroU64 ( IRAtom* e )
915     {
916        return
917           toBool( e->tag == Iex_Const
918                   && e->Iex.Const.con->tag == Ico_U64
919                   && e->Iex.Const.con->Ico.U64 == 0 );
920     }
921     
922     static IRAtom* doCmpORD ( MCEnv*  mce,
923                               IROp    cmp_op,
924                               IRAtom* xxhash, IRAtom* yyhash, 
925                               IRAtom* xx,     IRAtom* yy )
926     {
927        Bool   m64    = cmp_op == Iop_CmpORD64S || cmp_op == Iop_CmpORD64U;
928        Bool   syned  = cmp_op == Iop_CmpORD64S || cmp_op == Iop_CmpORD32S;
929        IROp   opOR   = m64 ? Iop_Or64  : Iop_Or32;
930        IROp   opAND  = m64 ? Iop_And64 : Iop_And32;
931        IROp   opSHL  = m64 ? Iop_Shl64 : Iop_Shl32;
932        IROp   opSHR  = m64 ? Iop_Shr64 : Iop_Shr32;
933        IRType ty     = m64 ? Ity_I64   : Ity_I32;
934        Int    width  = m64 ? 64        : 32;
935     
936        Bool (*isZero)(IRAtom*) = m64 ? isZeroU64 : isZeroU32;
937     
938        IRAtom* threeLeft1 = NULL;
939        IRAtom* sevenLeft1 = NULL;
940     
941        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,xxhash));
942        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,yyhash));
943        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,xx));
944        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,yy));
945        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(xxhash,xx));
946        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(yyhash,yy));
947        tl_assert(cmp_op == Iop_CmpORD32S || cmp_op == Iop_CmpORD32U
948                  || cmp_op == Iop_CmpORD64S || cmp_op == Iop_CmpORD64U);
949     
950        if (0) {
951           ppIROp(cmp_op); VG_(printf)(" "); 
952           ppIRExpr(xx); VG_(printf)(" "); ppIRExpr( yy ); VG_(printf)("\n");
953        }
954     
955        if (syned && isZero(yy)) {
956           /* fancy interpretation */
957           /* if yy is zero, then it must be fully defined (zero#). */
958           tl_assert(isZero(yyhash));
959           threeLeft1 = m64 ? mkU64(3<<1) : mkU32(3<<1);
960           return
961              binop(
962                 opOR,
963                 assignNew(
964                    'V', mce,ty,
965                    binop(
966                       opAND,
967                       mkPCastTo(mce,ty, xxhash), 
968                       threeLeft1
969                    )),
970                 assignNew(
971                    'V', mce,ty,
972                    binop(
973                       opSHL,
974                       assignNew(
975                          'V', mce,ty,
976                          binop(opSHR, xxhash, mkU8(width-1))),
977                       mkU8(3)
978                    ))
979     	 );
980        } else {
981           /* standard interpretation */
982           sevenLeft1 = m64 ? mkU64(7<<1) : mkU32(7<<1);
983           return 
984              binop( 
985                 opAND, 
986                 mkPCastTo( mce,ty,
987                            mkUifU(mce,ty, xxhash,yyhash)),
988                 sevenLeft1
989              );
990        }
991     }

994     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
995     /*--- Emit a test and complaint if something is undefined. ---*/
996     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
997     
998     static IRAtom* schemeE ( MCEnv* mce, IRExpr* e ); /* fwds */
999     
1000     
1001     /* Set the annotations on a dirty helper to indicate that the stack
1002        pointer and instruction pointers might be read.  This is the
1003        behaviour of all 'emit-a-complaint' style functions we might
1004        call. */
1005     
1006     static void setHelperAnns ( MCEnv* mce, IRDirty* di ) {
1007        di->nFxState = 2;
1008        di->fxState[0].fx     = Ifx_Read;
1009        di->fxState[0].offset = mce->layout->offset_SP;
1010        di->fxState[0].size   = mce->layout->sizeof_SP;
1011        di->fxState[1].fx     = Ifx_Read;
1012        di->fxState[1].offset = mce->layout->offset_IP;
1013        di->fxState[1].size   = mce->layout->sizeof_IP;
1014     }
1015     
1016     
1017     /* Check the supplied **original** atom for undefinedness, and emit a
1018        complaint if so.  Once that happens, mark it as defined.  This is
1019        possible because the atom is either a tmp or literal.  If it's a
1020        tmp, it will be shadowed by a tmp, and so we can set the shadow to
1021        be defined.  In fact as mentioned above, we will have to allocate a
1022        new tmp to carry the new 'defined' shadow value, and update the
1023        original->tmp mapping accordingly; we cannot simply assign a new
1024        value to an existing shadow tmp as this breaks SSAness -- resulting
1025        in the post-instrumentation sanity checker spluttering in disapproval. 
1026     */
1027     static void complainIfUndefined ( MCEnv* mce, IRAtom* atom )
1028     {
1029        IRAtom*  vatom;
1030        IRType   ty;
1031        Int      sz;
1032        IRDirty* di;
1033        IRAtom*  cond;
1034        IRAtom*  origin;
1035        void*    fn;
1036        HChar*   nm;
1037        IRExpr** args;
1038        Int      nargs;
1039     
1040        // Don't do V bit tests if we're not reporting undefined value errors.
1041        if (MC_(clo_mc_level) == 1)
1042           return;
1043     
1044        /* Since the original expression is atomic, there's no duplicated
1045           work generated by making multiple V-expressions for it.  So we
1046           don't really care about the possibility that someone else may
1047           also create a V-interpretion for it. */
1048        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce, atom));
1049        vatom = expr2vbits( mce, atom );
1050        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce, vatom));
1051        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(atom, vatom));
1052     
1053        ty = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, vatom);
1054     
1055        /* sz is only used for constructing the error message */
1056        sz = ty==Ity_I1 ? 0 : sizeofIRType(ty);
1057     
1058        cond = mkPCastTo( mce, Ity_I1, vatom );
1059        /* cond will be 0 if all defined, and 1 if any not defined. */
1060     
1061        /* Get the origin info for the value we are about to check.  At
1062           least, if we are doing origin tracking.  If not, use a dummy
1063           zero origin. */
1064        if (MC_(clo_mc_level) == 3) {
1065           origin = schemeE( mce, atom );
1066           if (mce->hWordTy == Ity_I64) {
1067              origin = assignNew( 'B', mce, Ity_I64, unop(Iop_32Uto64, origin) );
1068           }
1069        } else {
1070           origin = NULL;
1071        }
1072     
1073        fn    = NULL;
1074        nm    = NULL;
1075        args  = NULL;
1076        nargs = -1;
1077     
1078        switch (sz) {
1079           case 0:
1080              if (origin) {
1081                 fn    = &MC_(helperc_value_check0_fail_w_o);
1082                 nm    = "MC_(helperc_value_check0_fail_w_o)";
1083                 args  = mkIRExprVec_1(origin);
1084                 nargs = 1;
1085              } else {
1086                 fn    = &MC_(helperc_value_check0_fail_no_o);
1087                 nm    = "MC_(helperc_value_check0_fail_no_o)";
1088                 args  = mkIRExprVec_0();
1089                 nargs = 0;
1090              }
1091              break;
1092           case 1:
1093              if (origin) {
1094                 fn    = &MC_(helperc_value_check1_fail_w_o);
1095                 nm    = "MC_(helperc_value_check1_fail_w_o)";
1096                 args  = mkIRExprVec_1(origin);
1097                 nargs = 1;
1098              } else {
1099                 fn    = &MC_(helperc_value_check1_fail_no_o);
1100                 nm    = "MC_(helperc_value_check1_fail_no_o)";
1101                 args  = mkIRExprVec_0();
1102                 nargs = 0;
1103              }
1104              break;
1105           case 4:
1106              if (origin) {
1107                 fn    = &MC_(helperc_value_check4_fail_w_o);
1108                 nm    = "MC_(helperc_value_check4_fail_w_o)";
1109                 args  = mkIRExprVec_1(origin);
1110                 nargs = 1;
1111              } else {
1112                 fn    = &MC_(helperc_value_check4_fail_no_o);
1113                 nm    = "MC_(helperc_value_check4_fail_no_o)";
1114                 args  = mkIRExprVec_0();
1115                 nargs = 0;
1116              }
1117              break;
1118           case 8:
1119              if (origin) {
1120                 fn    = &MC_(helperc_value_check8_fail_w_o);
1121                 nm    = "MC_(helperc_value_check8_fail_w_o)";
1122                 args  = mkIRExprVec_1(origin);
1123                 nargs = 1;
1124              } else {
1125                 fn    = &MC_(helperc_value_check8_fail_no_o);
1126                 nm    = "MC_(helperc_value_check8_fail_no_o)";
1127                 args  = mkIRExprVec_0();
1128                 nargs = 0;
1129              }
1130              break;
1131           case 2:
1132           case 16:
1133              if (origin) {
1134                 fn    = &MC_(helperc_value_checkN_fail_w_o);
1135                 nm    = "MC_(helperc_value_checkN_fail_w_o)";
1136                 args  = mkIRExprVec_2( mkIRExpr_HWord( sz ), origin);
1137                 nargs = 2;
1138              } else {
1139                 fn    = &MC_(helperc_value_checkN_fail_no_o);
1140                 nm    = "MC_(helperc_value_checkN_fail_no_o)";
1141                 args  = mkIRExprVec_1( mkIRExpr_HWord( sz ) );
1142                 nargs = 1;
1143              }
1144              break;
1145           default:
1146              VG_(tool_panic)("unexpected szB");
1147        }
1148     
1149        tl_assert(fn);
1150        tl_assert(nm);
1151        tl_assert(args);
1152        tl_assert(nargs >= 0 && nargs <= 2);
1153        tl_assert( (MC_(clo_mc_level) == 3 && origin != NULL)
1154                   || (MC_(clo_mc_level) == 2 && origin == NULL) );
1155     
1156        di = unsafeIRDirty_0_N( nargs/*regparms*/, nm, 
1157                                VG_(fnptr_to_fnentry)( fn ), args );
1158        di->guard = cond;
1159        setHelperAnns( mce, di );
1160        stmt( 'V', mce, IRStmt_Dirty(di));
1161     
1162        /* Set the shadow tmp to be defined.  First, update the
1163           orig->shadow tmp mapping to reflect the fact that this shadow is
1164           getting a new value. */
1165        tl_assert(isIRAtom(vatom));
1166        /* sameKindedAtoms ... */
1167        if (vatom->tag == Iex_RdTmp) {
1168           tl_assert(atom->tag == Iex_RdTmp);
1169           newShadowTmpV(mce, atom->Iex.RdTmp.tmp);
1170           assign('V', mce, findShadowTmpV(mce, atom->Iex.RdTmp.tmp), 
1171                            definedOfType(ty));
1172        }
1173     }
1174     
1175     
1176     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
1177     /*--- Shadowing PUTs/GETs, and indexed variants thereof    ---*/
1178     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
1179     
1180     /* Examine the always-defined sections declared in layout to see if
1181        the (offset,size) section is within one.  Note, is is an error to
1182        partially fall into such a region: (offset,size) should either be
1183        completely in such a region or completely not-in such a region.  
1184     */
1185     static Bool isAlwaysDefd ( MCEnv* mce, Int offset, Int size )
1186     {
1187        Int minoffD, maxoffD, i;
1188        Int minoff = offset;
1189        Int maxoff = minoff + size - 1;
1190        tl_assert((minoff & ~0xFFFF) == 0);
1191        tl_assert((maxoff & ~0xFFFF) == 0);
1192     
1193        for (i = 0; i < mce->layout->n_alwaysDefd; i++) {
1194           minoffD = mce->layout->alwaysDefd[i].offset;
1195           maxoffD = minoffD + mce->layout->alwaysDefd[i].size - 1;
1196           tl_assert((minoffD & ~0xFFFF) == 0);
1197           tl_assert((maxoffD & ~0xFFFF) == 0);
1198     
1199           if (maxoff < minoffD || maxoffD < minoff)
1200              continue; /* no overlap */
1201           if (minoff >= minoffD && maxoff <= maxoffD)
1202              return True; /* completely contained in an always-defd section */
1203     
1204           VG_(tool_panic)("memcheck:isAlwaysDefd:partial overlap");
1205        }
1206        return False; /* could not find any containing section */
1207     }
1208     
1209     
1210     /* Generate into bb suitable actions to shadow this Put.  If the state
1211        slice is marked 'always defined', do nothing.  Otherwise, write the
1212        supplied V bits to the shadow state.  We can pass in either an
1213        original atom or a V-atom, but not both.  In the former case the
1214        relevant V-bits are then generated from the original.
1215     */
1216     static
1217     void do_shadow_PUT ( MCEnv* mce,  Int offset, 
1218                          IRAtom* atom, IRAtom* vatom )
1219     {
1220        IRType ty;
1221     
1222        // Don't do shadow PUTs if we're not doing undefined value checking.
1223        // Their absence lets Vex's optimiser remove all the shadow computation
1224        // that they depend on, which includes GETs of the shadow registers.
1225        if (MC_(clo_mc_level) == 1)
1226           return;
1227        
1228        if (atom) {
1229           tl_assert(!vatom);
1230           tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce, atom));
1231           vatom = expr2vbits( mce, atom );
1232        } else {
1233           tl_assert(vatom);
1234           tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce, vatom));
1235        }
1236     
1237        ty = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, vatom);
1238        tl_assert(ty != Ity_I1);
1239        tl_assert(ty != Ity_I128);
1240        if (isAlwaysDefd(mce, offset, sizeofIRType(ty))) {
1241           /* later: no ... */
1242           /* emit code to emit a complaint if any of the vbits are 1. */
1243           /* complainIfUndefined(mce, atom); */
1244        } else {
1245           /* Do a plain shadow Put. */
1246           stmt( 'V', mce, IRStmt_Put( offset + mce->layout->total_sizeB, vatom ) );
1247        }
1248     }
1249     
1250     
1251     /* Return an expression which contains the V bits corresponding to the
1252        given GETI (passed in in pieces). 
1253     */
1254     static
1255     void do_shadow_PUTI ( MCEnv* mce, 
1256                           IRRegArray* descr, 
1257                           IRAtom* ix, Int bias, IRAtom* atom )
1258     {
1259        IRAtom* vatom;
1260        IRType  ty, tyS;
1261        Int     arrSize;;
1262     
1263        // Don't do shadow PUTIs if we're not doing undefined value checking.
1264        // Their absence lets Vex's optimiser remove all the shadow computation
1265        // that they depend on, which includes GETIs of the shadow registers.
1266        if (MC_(clo_mc_level) == 1)
1267           return;
1268        
1269        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,atom));
1270        vatom = expr2vbits( mce, atom );
1271        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(atom, vatom));
1272        ty   = descr->elemTy;
1273        tyS  = shadowTypeV(ty);
1274        arrSize = descr->nElems * sizeofIRType(ty);
1275        tl_assert(ty != Ity_I1);
1276        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,ix));
1277        complainIfUndefined(mce,ix);
1278        if (isAlwaysDefd(mce, descr->base, arrSize)) {
1279           /* later: no ... */
1280           /* emit code to emit a complaint if any of the vbits are 1. */
1281           /* complainIfUndefined(mce, atom); */
1282        } else {
1283           /* Do a cloned version of the Put that refers to the shadow
1284              area. */
1285           IRRegArray* new_descr 
1286              = mkIRRegArray( descr->base + mce->layout->total_sizeB, 
1287                              tyS, descr->nElems);
1288           stmt( 'V', mce, IRStmt_PutI( new_descr, ix, bias, vatom ));
1289        }
1290     }
1291     
1292     
1293     /* Return an expression which contains the V bits corresponding to the
1294        given GET (passed in in pieces). 
1295     */
1296     static 
1297     IRExpr* shadow_GET ( MCEnv* mce, Int offset, IRType ty )
1298     {
1299        IRType tyS = shadowTypeV(ty);
1300        tl_assert(ty != Ity_I1);
1301        tl_assert(ty != Ity_I128);
1302        if (isAlwaysDefd(mce, offset, sizeofIRType(ty))) {
1303           /* Always defined, return all zeroes of the relevant type */
1304           return definedOfType(tyS);
1305        } else {
1306           /* return a cloned version of the Get that refers to the shadow
1307              area. */
1308           /* FIXME: this isn't an atom! */
1309           return IRExpr_Get( offset + mce->layout->total_sizeB, tyS );
1310        }
1311     }
1312     
1313     
1314     /* Return an expression which contains the V bits corresponding to the
1315        given GETI (passed in in pieces). 
1316     */
1317     static
1318     IRExpr* shadow_GETI ( MCEnv* mce, 
1319                           IRRegArray* descr, IRAtom* ix, Int bias )
1320     {
1321        IRType ty   = descr->elemTy;
1322        IRType tyS  = shadowTypeV(ty);
1323        Int arrSize = descr->nElems * sizeofIRType(ty);
1324        tl_assert(ty != Ity_I1);
1325        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,ix));
1326        complainIfUndefined(mce,ix);
1327        if (isAlwaysDefd(mce, descr->base, arrSize)) {
1328           /* Always defined, return all zeroes of the relevant type */
1329           return definedOfType(tyS);
1330        } else {
1331           /* return a cloned version of the Get that refers to the shadow
1332              area. */
1333           IRRegArray* new_descr 
1334              = mkIRRegArray( descr->base + mce->layout->total_sizeB, 
1335                              tyS, descr->nElems);
1336           return IRExpr_GetI( new_descr, ix, bias );
1337        }
1338     }

1341     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
1342     /*--- Generating approximations for unknown operations,    ---*/
1343     /*--- using lazy-propagate semantics                       ---*/
1344     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
1345     
1346     /* Lazy propagation of undefinedness from two values, resulting in the
1347        specified shadow type. 
1348     */
1349     static
1350     IRAtom* mkLazy2 ( MCEnv* mce, IRType finalVty, IRAtom* va1, IRAtom* va2 )
1351     {
1352        IRAtom* at;
1353        IRType t1 = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, va1);
1354        IRType t2 = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, va2);
1355        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,va1));
1356        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,va2));
1357     
1358        /* The general case is inefficient because PCast is an expensive
1359           operation.  Here are some special cases which use PCast only
1360           once rather than twice. */
1361     
1362        /* I64 x I64 -> I64 */
1363        if (t1 == Ity_I64 && t2 == Ity_I64 && finalVty == Ity_I64) {
1364           if (0) VG_(printf)("mkLazy2: I64 x I64 -> I64\n");
1365           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I64, va1, va2);
1366           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I64, at);
1367           return at;
1368        }
1369     
1370        /* I64 x I64 -> I32 */
1371        if (t1 == Ity_I64 && t2 == Ity_I64 && finalVty == Ity_I32) {
1372           if (0) VG_(printf)("mkLazy2: I64 x I64 -> I32\n");
1373           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I64, va1, va2);
1374           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I32, at);
1375           return at;
1376        }
1377     
1378        if (0) {
1379           VG_(printf)("mkLazy2 ");
1380           ppIRType(t1);
1381           VG_(printf)("_");
1382           ppIRType(t2);
1383           VG_(printf)("_");
1384           ppIRType(finalVty);
1385           VG_(printf)("\n");
1386        }
1387     
1388        /* General case: force everything via 32-bit intermediaries. */
1389        at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I32, va1);
1390        at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I32, at, mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I32, va2));
1391        at = mkPCastTo(mce, finalVty, at);
1392        return at;
1393     }
1394     
1395     
1396     /* 3-arg version of the above. */
1397     static
1398     IRAtom* mkLazy3 ( MCEnv* mce, IRType finalVty, 
1399                       IRAtom* va1, IRAtom* va2, IRAtom* va3 )
1400     {
1401        IRAtom* at;
1402        IRType t1 = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, va1);
1403        IRType t2 = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, va2);
1404        IRType t3 = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, va3);
1405        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,va1));
1406        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,va2));
1407        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,va3));
1408     
1409        /* The general case is inefficient because PCast is an expensive
1410           operation.  Here are some special cases which use PCast only
1411           twice rather than three times. */
1412     
1413        /* I32 x I64 x I64 -> I64 */
1414        /* Standard FP idiom: rm x FParg1 x FParg2 -> FPresult */
1415        if (t1 == Ity_I32 && t2 == Ity_I64 && t3 == Ity_I64 
1416            && finalVty == Ity_I64) {
1417           if (0) VG_(printf)("mkLazy3: I32 x I64 x I64 -> I64\n");
1418           /* Widen 1st arg to I64.  Since 1st arg is typically a rounding
1419              mode indication which is fully defined, this should get
1420              folded out later. */
1421           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I64, va1);
1422           /* Now fold in 2nd and 3rd args. */
1423           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I64, at, va2);
1424           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I64, at, va3);
1425           /* and PCast once again. */
1426           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I64, at);
1427           return at;
1428        }
1429     
1430        /* I32 x I64 x I64 -> I32 */
1431        if (t1 == Ity_I32 && t2 == Ity_I64 && t3 == Ity_I64 
1432            && finalVty == Ity_I32) {
1433           if (0) VG_(printf)("mkLazy3: I32 x I64 x I64 -> I32\n");
1434           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I64, va1);
1435           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I64, at, va2);
1436           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I64, at, va3);
1437           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I32, at);
1438           return at;
1439        }
1440     
1441        /* I32 x I32 x I32 -> I32 */
1442        /* 32-bit FP idiom, as (eg) happens on ARM */
1443        if (t1 == Ity_I32 && t2 == Ity_I32 && t3 == Ity_I32 
1444            && finalVty == Ity_I32) {
1445           if (0) VG_(printf)("mkLazy3: I32 x I32 x I32 -> I32\n");
1446           at = va1;
1447           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I32, at, va2);
1448           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I32, at, va3);
1449           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I32, at);
1450           return at;
1451        }
1452     
1453        /* I32 x I128 x I128 -> I128 */
1454        /* Standard FP idiom: rm x FParg1 x FParg2 -> FPresult */
1455        if (t1 == Ity_I32 && t2 == Ity_I128 && t3 == Ity_I128
1456            && finalVty == Ity_I128) {
1457           if (0) VG_(printf)("mkLazy3: I32 x I128 x I128 -> I128\n");
1458           /* Widen 1st arg to I128.  Since 1st arg is typically a rounding
1459              mode indication which is fully defined, this should get
1460              folded out later. */
1461           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I128, va1);
1462           /* Now fold in 2nd and 3rd args. */
1463           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I128, at, va2);
1464           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I128, at, va3);
1465           /* and PCast once again. */
1466           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I128, at);
1467           return at;
1468        }
1469        if (1) {
1470           VG_(printf)("mkLazy3: ");
1471           ppIRType(t1);
1472           VG_(printf)(" x ");
1473           ppIRType(t2);
1474           VG_(printf)(" x ");
1475           ppIRType(t3);
1476           VG_(printf)(" -> ");
1477           ppIRType(finalVty);
1478           VG_(printf)("\n");
1479        }
1480     
1481        tl_assert(0);
1482        /* General case: force everything via 32-bit intermediaries. */
1483        /*
1484        at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I32, va1);
1485        at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I32, at, mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I32, va2));
1486        at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I32, at, mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I32, va3));
1487        at = mkPCastTo(mce, finalVty, at);
1488        return at;
1489        */
1490     }

1493     /* 4-arg version of the above. */
1494     static
1495     IRAtom* mkLazy4 ( MCEnv* mce, IRType finalVty, 
1496                       IRAtom* va1, IRAtom* va2, IRAtom* va3, IRAtom* va4 )
1497     {
1498        IRAtom* at;
1499        IRType t1 = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, va1);
1500        IRType t2 = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, va2);
1501        IRType t3 = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, va3);
1502        IRType t4 = typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, va4);
1503        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,va1));
1504        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,va2));
1505        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,va3));
1506        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,va4));
1507     
1508        /* The general case is inefficient because PCast is an expensive
1509           operation.  Here are some special cases which use PCast only
1510           twice rather than three times. */
1511     
1512        /* I32 x I64 x I64 x I64 -> I64 */
1513        /* Standard FP idiom: rm x FParg1 x FParg2 x FParg3 -> FPresult */
1514        if (t1 == Ity_I32 && t2 == Ity_I64 && t3 == Ity_I64 && t4 == Ity_I64
1515            && finalVty == Ity_I64) {
1516           if (0) VG_(printf)("mkLazy4: I32 x I64 x I64 x I64 -> I64\n");
1517           /* Widen 1st arg to I64.  Since 1st arg is typically a rounding
1518              mode indication which is fully defined, this should get
1519              folded out later. */
1520           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I64, va1);
1521           /* Now fold in 2nd, 3rd, 4th args. */
1522           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I64, at, va2);
1523           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I64, at, va3);
1524           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I64, at, va4);
1525           /* and PCast once again. */
1526           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I64, at);
1527           return at;
1528        }
1529        /* I32 x I32 x I32 x I32 -> I32 */
1530        /* Standard FP idiom: rm x FParg1 x FParg2 x FParg3 -> FPresult */
1531        if (t1 == Ity_I32 && t2 == Ity_I32 && t3 == Ity_I32 && t4 == Ity_I32
1532            && finalVty == Ity_I32) {
1533           if (0) VG_(printf)("mkLazy4: I32 x I32 x I32 x I32 -> I32\n");
1534           at = va1;
1535           /* Now fold in 2nd, 3rd, 4th args. */
1536           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I32, at, va2);
1537           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I32, at, va3);
1538           at = mkUifU(mce, Ity_I32, at, va4);
1539           at = mkPCastTo(mce, Ity_I32, at);
1540           return at;
1541        }
1542     
1543        if (1) {
1544           VG_(printf)("mkLazy4: ");
1545           ppIRType(t1);
1546           VG_(printf)(" x ");
1547           ppIRType(t2);
1548           VG_(printf)(" x ");
1549           ppIRType(t3);
1550           VG_(printf)(" x ");
1551           ppIRType(t4);
1552           VG_(printf)(" -> ");
1553           ppIRType(finalVty);
1554           VG_(printf)("\n");
1555        }
1556     
1557        tl_assert(0);
1558     }

1560     
1561     /* Do the lazy propagation game from a null-terminated vector of
1562        atoms.  This is presumably the arguments to a helper call, so the
1563        IRCallee info is also supplied in order that we can know which
1564        arguments should be ignored (via the .mcx_mask field). 
1565     */
1566     static
1567     IRAtom* mkLazyN ( MCEnv* mce, 
1568                       IRAtom** exprvec, IRType finalVtype, IRCallee* cee )
1569     {
1570        Int     i;
1571        IRAtom* here;
1572        IRAtom* curr;
1573        IRType  mergeTy;
1574        IRType  mergeTy64 = True;
1575     
1576        /* Decide on the type of the merge intermediary.  If all relevant
1577           args are I64, then it's I64.  In all other circumstances, use
1578           I32. */
1579        for (i = 0; exprvec[i]; i++) {
1580           tl_assert(i < 32);
1581           tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce, exprvec[i]));
1582           if (cee->mcx_mask & (1<<i))
1583              continue;
1584           if (typeOfIRExpr(mce->sb->tyenv, exprvec[i]) != Ity_I64)
1585              mergeTy64 = False;
1586        }
1587     
1588        mergeTy = mergeTy64  ? Ity_I64  : Ity_I32;
1589        curr    = definedOfType(mergeTy);
1590     
1591        for (i = 0; exprvec[i]; i++) {
1592           tl_assert(i < 32);
1593           tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce, exprvec[i]));
1594           /* Only take notice of this arg if the callee's mc-exclusion
1595              mask does not say it is to be excluded. */
1596           if (cee->mcx_mask & (1<<i)) {
1597              /* the arg is to be excluded from definedness checking.  Do
1598                 nothing. */
1599              if (0) VG_(printf)("excluding %s(%d)\n", cee->name, i);
1600           } else {
1601              /* calculate the arg's definedness, and pessimistically merge
1602                 it in. */
1603              here = mkPCastTo( mce, mergeTy, expr2vbits(mce, exprvec[i]) );
1604              curr = mergeTy64 
1605                        ? mkUifU64(mce, here, curr)
1606                        : mkUifU32(mce, here, curr);
1607           }
1608        }
1609        return mkPCastTo(mce, finalVtype, curr );
1610     }

1613     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
1614     /*--- Generating expensive sequences for exact carry-chain ---*/
1615     /*--- propagation in add/sub and related operations.       ---*/
1616     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
1617     
1618     static
1619     IRAtom* expensiveAddSub ( MCEnv*  mce,
1620                               Bool    add,
1621                               IRType  ty,
1622                               IRAtom* qaa, IRAtom* qbb, 
1623                               IRAtom* aa,  IRAtom* bb )
1624     {
1625        IRAtom *a_min, *b_min, *a_max, *b_max;
1626        IROp   opAND, opOR, opXOR, opNOT, opADD, opSUB;
1627     
1628        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,qaa));
1629        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,qbb));
1630        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,aa));
1631        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,bb));
1632        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(qaa,aa));
1633        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(qbb,bb));
1634     
1635        switch (ty) {
1636           case Ity_I32:
1637              opAND = Iop_And32;
1638              opOR  = Iop_Or32;
1639              opXOR = Iop_Xor32;
1640              opNOT = Iop_Not32;
1641              opADD = Iop_Add32;
1642              opSUB = Iop_Sub32;
1643              break;
1644           case Ity_I64:
1645              opAND = Iop_And64;
1646              opOR  = Iop_Or64;
1647              opXOR = Iop_Xor64;
1648              opNOT = Iop_Not64;
1649              opADD = Iop_Add64;
1650              opSUB = Iop_Sub64;
1651              break;
1652           default:
1653              VG_(tool_panic)("expensiveAddSub");
1654        }
1655     
1656        // a_min = aa & ~qaa
1657        a_min = assignNew('V', mce,ty, 
1658                          binop(opAND, aa,
1659                                       assignNew('V', mce,ty, unop(opNOT, qaa))));
1660     
1661        // b_min = bb & ~qbb
1662        b_min = assignNew('V', mce,ty, 
1663                          binop(opAND, bb,
1664                                       assignNew('V', mce,ty, unop(opNOT, qbb))));
1665     
1666        // a_max = aa | qaa
1667        a_max = assignNew('V', mce,ty, binop(opOR, aa, qaa));
1668     
1669        // b_max = bb | qbb
1670        b_max = assignNew('V', mce,ty, binop(opOR, bb, qbb));
1671     
1672        if (add) {
1673           // result = (qaa | qbb) | ((a_min + b_min) ^ (a_max + b_max))
1674           return
1675           assignNew('V', mce,ty,
1676              binop( opOR,
1677                     assignNew('V', mce,ty, binop(opOR, qaa, qbb)),
1678                     assignNew('V', mce,ty, 
1679                        binop( opXOR, 
1680                               assignNew('V', mce,ty, binop(opADD, a_min, b_min)),
1681                               assignNew('V', mce,ty, binop(opADD, a_max, b_max))
1682                        )
1683                     )
1684              )
1685           );
1686        } else {
1687           // result = (qaa | qbb) | ((a_min - b_max) ^ (a_max + b_min))
1688           return
1689           assignNew('V', mce,ty,
1690              binop( opOR,
1691                     assignNew('V', mce,ty, binop(opOR, qaa, qbb)),
1692                     assignNew('V', mce,ty, 
1693                        binop( opXOR, 
1694                               assignNew('V', mce,ty, binop(opSUB, a_min, b_max)),
1695                               assignNew('V', mce,ty, binop(opSUB, a_max, b_min))
1696                        )
1697                     )
1698              )
1699           );
1700        }
1701     
1702     }

1705     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
1706     /*--- Scalar shifts.                                       ---*/
1707     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
1708     
1709     /* Produce an interpretation for (aa << bb) (or >>s, >>u).  The basic
1710        idea is to shift the definedness bits by the original shift amount.
1711        This introduces 0s ("defined") in new positions for left shifts and
1712        unsigned right shifts, and copies the top definedness bit for
1713        signed right shifts.  So, conveniently, applying the original shift
1714        operator to the definedness bits for the left arg is exactly the
1715        right thing to do:
1716     
1717           (qaa << bb)
1718     
1719        However if the shift amount is undefined then the whole result
1720        is undefined.  Hence need:
1721     
1722           (qaa << bb) `UifU` PCast(qbb)
1723     
1724        If the shift amount bb is a literal than qbb will say 'all defined'
1725        and the UifU and PCast will get folded out by post-instrumentation
1726        optimisation.
1727     */
1728     static IRAtom* scalarShift ( MCEnv*  mce,
1729                                  IRType  ty,
1730                                  IROp    original_op,
1731                                  IRAtom* qaa, IRAtom* qbb, 
1732                                  IRAtom* aa,  IRAtom* bb )
1733     {
1734        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,qaa));
1735        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,qbb));
1736        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,aa));
1737        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,bb));
1738        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(qaa,aa));
1739        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(qbb,bb));
1740        return 
1741           assignNew(
1742              'V', mce, ty,
1743              mkUifU( mce, ty,
1744                      assignNew('V', mce, ty, binop(original_op, qaa, bb)),
1745                      mkPCastTo(mce, ty, qbb)
1746              )
1747        );
1748     }

1803     /* Here's a simple scheme capable of handling ops derived from SSE1
1804        code and while only generating ops that can be efficiently
1805        implemented in SSE1. */
1806     
1807     /* All-lanes versions are straightforward:
1808     
1809        binary32Fx4(x,y)   ==> PCast32x4(UifUV128(x#,y#))
1810     
1811        unary32Fx4(x,y)    ==> PCast32x4(x#)
1812     
1813        Lowest-lane-only versions are more complex:
1814     
1815        binary32F0x4(x,y)  ==> SetV128lo32(
1816                                  x#, 
1817                                  PCast32(V128to32(UifUV128(x#,y#))) 
1818                               )
1819     
1820        This is perhaps not so obvious.  In particular, it's faster to
1821        do a V128-bit UifU and then take the bottom 32 bits than the more
1822        obvious scheme of taking the bottom 32 bits of each operand
1823        and doing a 32-bit UifU.  Basically since UifU is fast and 
1824        chopping lanes off vector values is slow.
1825     
1826        Finally:
1827     
1828        unary32F0x4(x)     ==> SetV128lo32(
1829                                  x#, 
1830                                  PCast32(V128to32(x#)) 
1831                               )
1832     
1833        Where:
1834     
1835        PCast32(v#)   = 1Sto32(CmpNE32(v#,0))
1836        PCast32x4(v#) = CmpNEZ32x4(v#)
1837     */
1838     
1839     static
1840     IRAtom* binary32Fx4 ( MCEnv* mce, IRAtom* vatomX, IRAtom* vatomY )
1841     {
1842        IRAtom* at;
1843        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce, vatomX));
1844        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce, vatomY));
1845        at = mkUifUV128(mce, vatomX, vatomY);
1846        at = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_V128, mkPCast32x4(mce, at));
1847        return at;
1848     }
1849     
1850     static
1851     IRAtom* unary32Fx4 ( MCEnv* mce, IRAtom* vatomX )
1852     {
1853        IRAtom* at;
1854        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce, vatomX));
1855        at = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_V128, mkPCast32x4(mce, vatomX));
1856        return at;
1857     }
1858     
1859     static

1951     /* --- --- Vector saturated narrowing --- --- */
1952     
1953     /* This is quite subtle.  What to do is simple:
1954     
1955        Let the original narrowing op be QNarrowW{S,U}xN.  Produce:
1956     
1957           the-narrowing-op( PCastWxN(vatom1), PCastWxN(vatom2))
1958     
1959        Why this is right is not so simple.  Consider a lane in the args,
1960        vatom1 or 2, doesn't matter.
1961     
1962        After the PCast, that lane is all 0s (defined) or all
1963        1s(undefined).
1964     
1965        Both signed and unsigned saturating narrowing of all 0s produces
1966        all 0s, which is what we want.
1967     
1968        The all-1s case is more complex.  Unsigned narrowing interprets an
1969        all-1s input as the largest unsigned integer, and so produces all
1970        1s as a result since that is the largest unsigned value at the
1971        smaller width.
1972     
1973        Signed narrowing interprets all 1s as -1.  Fortunately, -1 narrows
1974        to -1, so we still wind up with all 1s at the smaller width.
1975     
1976        So: In short, pessimise the args, then apply the original narrowing
1977        op.
1978     */
1979     static
1980     IRAtom* vectorNarrowV128 ( MCEnv* mce, IROp narrow_op, 
1981                               IRAtom* vatom1, IRAtom* vatom2)
1982     {
1983        IRAtom *at1, *at2, *at3;
1984        IRAtom* (*pcast)( MCEnv*, IRAtom* );
1985        switch (narrow_op) {
1986           case Iop_QNarrow32Sx4: pcast = mkPCast32x4; break;
1987           case Iop_QNarrow32Ux4: pcast = mkPCast32x4; break;
1988           case Iop_QNarrow16Sx8: pcast = mkPCast16x8; break;
1989           case Iop_QNarrow16Ux8: pcast = mkPCast16x8; break;
1990           default: VG_(tool_panic)("vectorNarrowV128");
1991        }
1992        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vatom1));
1993        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vatom2));
1994        at1 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_V128, pcast(mce, vatom1));
1995        at2 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_V128, pcast(mce, vatom2));
1996        at3 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_V128, binop(narrow_op, at1, at2));
1997        return at3;
1998     }
1999     
2000     static
2001     IRAtom* vectorNarrow64 ( MCEnv* mce, IROp narrow_op, 
2002                              IRAtom* vatom1, IRAtom* vatom2)
2003     {
2004        IRAtom *at1, *at2, *at3;
2005        IRAtom* (*pcast)( MCEnv*, IRAtom* );
2006        switch (narrow_op) {
2007           case Iop_QNarrow32Sx2: pcast = mkPCast32x2; break;
2008           case Iop_QNarrow16Sx4: pcast = mkPCast16x4; break;
2009           case Iop_QNarrow16Ux4: pcast = mkPCast16x4; break;
2010           default: VG_(tool_panic)("vectorNarrow64");
2011        }
2012        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vatom1));
2013        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vatom2));
2014        at1 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, pcast(mce, vatom1));
2015        at2 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, pcast(mce, vatom2));
2016        at3 = assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, binop(narrow_op, at1, at2));

2018     }

2171     /*--- Generate shadow values from all kinds of IRExprs.    ---*/
2172     /*------------------------------------------------------------*/
2173     
2174     static 
2175     IRAtom* expr2vbits_Qop ( MCEnv* mce,
2176                              IROp op,
2177                              IRAtom* atom1, IRAtom* atom2, 
2178                              IRAtom* atom3, IRAtom* atom4 )
2179     {
2180        IRAtom* vatom1 = expr2vbits( mce, atom1 );
2181        IRAtom* vatom2 = expr2vbits( mce, atom2 );
2182        IRAtom* vatom3 = expr2vbits( mce, atom3 );
2183        IRAtom* vatom4 = expr2vbits( mce, atom4 );
2184     
2185        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,atom1));
2186        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,atom2));
2187        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,atom3));
2188        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,atom4));
2189        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vatom1));
2190        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vatom2));
2191        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vatom3));
2192        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vatom4));
2193        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(atom1,vatom1));
2194        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(atom2,vatom2));
2195        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(atom3,vatom3));
2196        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(atom4,vatom4));
2197        switch (op) {
2198           case Iop_MAddF64:
2199           case Iop_MAddF64r32:
2200           case Iop_MSubF64:
2201           case Iop_MSubF64r32:
2202              /* I32(rm) x F64 x F64 x F64 -> F64 */
2203              return mkLazy4(mce, Ity_I64, vatom1, vatom2, vatom3, vatom4);
2204     
2205           case Iop_MAddF32:
2206           case Iop_MSubF32:
2207              /* I32(rm) x F32 x F32 x F32 -> F32 */
2208              return mkLazy4(mce, Ity_I32, vatom1, vatom2, vatom3, vatom4);
2209     
2210           default:
2211              ppIROp(op);
2212              VG_(tool_panic)("memcheck:expr2vbits_Qop");
2213        }
2214     }

2217     static 
2218     IRAtom* expr2vbits_Triop ( MCEnv* mce,
2219                                IROp op,
2220                                IRAtom* atom1, IRAtom* atom2, IRAtom* atom3 )
2221     {
2222        IRAtom* vatom1 = expr2vbits( mce, atom1 );
2223        IRAtom* vatom2 = expr2vbits( mce, atom2 );
2224        IRAtom* vatom3 = expr2vbits( mce, atom3 );
2225     
2226        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,atom1));
2227        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,atom2));
2228        tl_assert(isOriginalAtom(mce,atom3));
2229        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vatom1));
2230        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vatom2));
2231        tl_assert(isShadowAtom(mce,vatom3));
2232        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(atom1,vatom1));
2233        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(atom2,vatom2));
2234        tl_assert(sameKindedAtoms(atom3,vatom3));
2235        switch (op) {
2236           case Iop_AddF128:
2237           case Iop_SubF128:
2238           case Iop_MulF128:
2239           case Iop_DivF128:
2240              /* I32(rm) x F128 x F128 -> F128 */
2241              return mkLazy3(mce, Ity_I128, vatom1, vatom2, vatom3);
2242           case Iop_AddF64:
2243           case Iop_AddF64r32:
2244           case Iop_SubF64:
2245           case Iop_SubF64r32:
2246           case Iop_MulF64:
2247           case Iop_MulF64r32:
2248           case Iop_DivF64:
2249           case Iop_DivF64r32:
2250           case Iop_ScaleF64:
2251           case Iop_Yl2xF64:
2252           case Iop_Yl2xp1F64:
2253           case Iop_AtanF64:
2254           case Iop_PRemF64:
2255           case Iop_PRem1F64:
2256              /* I32(rm) x F64 x F64 -> F64 */
2257              return mkLazy3(mce, Ity_I64, vatom1, vatom2, vatom3);
2258           case Iop_PRemC3210F64:
2259           case Iop_PRem1C3210F64:
2260              /* I32(rm) x F64 x F64 -> I32 */
2261              return mkLazy3(mce, Ity_I32, vatom1, vatom2, vatom3);
2262           case Iop_AddF32:
2263           case Iop_SubF32:
2264           case Iop_MulF32:
2265           case Iop_DivF32:
2266              /* I32(rm) x F32 x F32 -> I32 */
2267              return mkLazy3(mce, Ity_I32, vatom1, vatom2, vatom3);
2268           case Iop_ExtractV128:
2269              complainIfUndefined(mce, atom3);
2270              return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_V128, triop(op, vatom1, vatom2, atom3));
2271           case Iop_Extract64:
2272              complainIfUndefined(mce, atom3);
2273              return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, triop(op, vatom1, vatom2, atom3));
2274           case Iop_SetElem8x8:
2275           case Iop_SetElem16x4:
2276           case Iop_SetElem32x2:
2277              complainIfUndefined(mce, atom2);
2278              return assignNew('V', mce, Ity_I64, triop(op, vatom1, atom2, vatom3));
2279           default:
2280              ppIROp(op);
2281              VG_(tool_panic)("memcheck:expr2vbits_Triop");
2282        }
2283     }

3129              return scalarShift( mce, Ity_I32, op, vatom1,vatom2, atom1,atom2 );
3130     
3131           case Iop_Shl16: case Iop_Shr16: case Iop_Sar16:
3132              return scalarShift( mce, Ity_I16, op, vatom1,vatom2, atom1,atom2 );
3133     
3134           case Iop_Shl8: case Iop_Shr8:
3135              return scalarShift( mce, Ity_I8, op, vatom1,vatom2, atom1,atom2 );
3136     
3137           case Iop_AndV128:
3138              uifu = mkUifUV128; difd = mkDifDV128; 
3139              and_or_ty = Ity_V128; improve = mkImproveANDV128; goto do_And_Or;
3140           case Iop_And64:
3141              uifu = mkUifU64; difd = mkDifD64; 
3142              and_or_ty = Ity_I64; improve = mkImproveAND64; goto do_And_Or;
3143           case Iop_And32:
3144              uifu = mkUifU32; difd = mkDifD32; 
3145              and_or_ty = Ity_I32; improve = mkImproveAND32; goto do_And_Or;
3146           case Iop_And16:
3147              uifu = mkUifU16; difd = mkDifD16; 
3148              and_or_ty = Ity_I16; improve = mkImproveAND16; goto do_And_Or;
3149           case Iop_And8:
3150              uifu = mkUifU8; difd = mkDifD8; 
3151              and_or_ty = Ity_I8; improve = mkImproveAND8; goto do_And_Or;
3152     
3153           case Iop_OrV128:
3154              uifu = mkUifUV128; difd = mkDifDV128; 
3155              and_or_ty = Ity_V128; improve = mkImproveORV128; goto do_And_Or;
3156           case Iop_Or64:
3157              uifu = mkUifU64; difd = mkDifD64; 
3158              and_or_ty = Ity_I64; improve = mkImproveOR64; goto do_And_Or;
3159           case Iop_Or32:
3160              uifu = mkUifU32; difd = mkDifD32; 
3161              and_or_ty = Ity_I32; improve = mkImproveOR32; goto do_And_Or;
3162           case Iop_Or16:
3163              uifu = mkUifU16; difd = mkDifD16; 
3164              and_or_ty = Ity_I16; improve = mkImproveOR16; goto do_And_Or;
3165           case Iop_Or8:
3166              uifu = mkUifU8; difd = mkDifD8; 
3167              and_or_ty = Ity_I8; improve = mkImproveOR8; goto do_And_Or;
3168     
3169           do_And_Or:
3170              return
3171              assignNew(
3172                 'V', mce, 
3173                 and_or_ty,
3174                 difd(mce, uifu(mce, vatom1, vatom2),
3175                           difd(mce, improve(mce, atom1, vatom1),
3176                                     improve(mce, atom2, vatom2) ) ) );
3177     
3178           case Iop_Xor8:
3179              return mkUifU8(mce, vatom1, vatom2);
3180           case Iop_Xor16:
3181              return mkUifU16(mce, vatom1, vatom2);
3182           case Iop_Xor32:
3183              return mkUifU32(mce, vatom1, vatom2);
3184           case Iop_Xor64:
3185              return mkUifU64(mce, vatom1, vatom2);
3186           case Iop_XorV128:
3187              return mkUifUV128(mce, vatom1, vatom2);
3188     
3189           default:
3190              ppIROp(op);
3191              VG_(tool_panic)("memcheck:expr2vbits_Binop");
3192        }
3193     }
